 {"id":"br-9bmtl","title":"Attention Feed Phase 4b1: Build comprehensive unit and integration coverage for the new operator loop","description":"# Why this bead exists
The earlier test bead covered the core feed, but it still left too much room for user-facing summary surfaces to be under-tested. If dashboard/terse and profile behavior are part of the product contract, they need deterministic automated coverage, not just manual spot-checking.

# Scope
1. Add deterministic unit tests for envelope serialization, cursor allocation, replay windows, eviction, mapping, derived signals, snapshot bootstrap, digest coalescing, wait conditions, profile resolution, and summary/view-model generation.
2. Add integration tests for CLI and server parity so the same underlying event looks materially the same across command and transport surfaces.
3. Add deterministic tests for dashboard/terse summary output, including quiet, interesting, action-required, degraded, and profile-specific cases.
4. Add command-chain tests for snapshot -> events/digest/wait/attention handoff where a full transcript-style e2e harness is not required.
5. Keep this bead focused on deterministic unit/integration verification; long-form transcript scenarios live in the paired e2e bead.

# Logging / artifact expectations
- Failed tests should log cursor ranges, matched conditions, suppression decisions, active profiles, transport mode, and summary bucket state.
- Golden/parity tests should emit diff-friendly diagnostics when payloads or terse/dashboard summaries drift.
- Integration tests should capture enough structured context to explain parity failures without immediate manual reproduction.
- Any shared summary/view-model regressions should print both the underlying signal snapshot and the rendered summary so future maintainers can see where divergence started.

# Acceptance criteria
- [ ] Core feed, snapshot bootstrap, digest, wait, attention, transport, profile, and dashboard/terse summary semantics are covered automatically at unit/integration level.
- [ ] Important failure modes such as expired cursor, unsupported replay window, partial observability, and contradictory profile/filter combinations have explicit automated coverage.
- [ ] Logs are detailed enough to debug failures without guesswork.

# Test commands that must pass before closing this bead
- `go build ./cmd/ntm`
- `go test -short ./...`
- package-targeted tests for `internal/robot/...`, `internal/serve/...`, `internal/events/...`, `internal/tracker/...`, and any dashboard/output packages touched by the feature","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":240,"created_at":"2026-03-21T00:49:21.798002184Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-21T09:29:18.898834689Z","closed_at":"2026-03-21T09:29:18.898377533Z","close_reason":"Comprehensive test coverage complete: operator loop cursor chaining, profile filtering, snapshot summary consistency, attention conditions, wait integration. Commits f63a1090, c7a1cdaa.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["attention-feed","phase-4","robot","tests","verification"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"br-9bmtl","depends_on_id":"br-6tzh9","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T00:49:29.031845838Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-9bmtl","depends_on_id":"br-7kigk","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T00:49:29.394483660Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-9bmtl","depends_on_id":"br-91gti","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T01:11:29.447157567Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-9bmtl","depends_on_id":"br-auag6","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T01:11:29.710446136Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-9bmtl","depends_on_id":"br-slg9g","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T00:57:17.871290905Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-9bmtl","depends_on_id":"br-t540i","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T00:49:29.761115149Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-9bmtl","depends_on_id":"br-tsqxo","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T00:49:28.667513894Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"br-a1ti3","title":"Overlay-Feed T7: Verify end-to-end overlay-feed integration and document invariants","description":"# Why this bead exists
The overlay/feed branch needs its own final verification gate for the same reason the core attention-feed initiative does: the question is not whether each sub-bead sounds plausible, but whether the whole human/agent handoff loop actually works coherently and leaves behind understandable artifacts for future maintainers.

# Scope
1. Verify the overlay/feed cold-start path when the feed is unavailable or empty.
2. Verify the warm path where real attention items, badge state, and overlay summaries agree.
3. Verify zoom/dismiss continuity events and cursor hints.
4. Verify cursor-targeted human handoff from an agent-facing attention response into the overlay.
5. Verify `assign --watch` workflow discoverability and overlay entry.
6. Confirm all documented invariants and non-goals remain true.
7. Confirm the overlay branch still degrades honestly when the feed is unavailable.
8. Leave behind a concise record of what commands/scenarios were run and where the most useful artifacts live.

# Invariants that must hold
- The overlay never becomes a second event source of truth.
- Human-originated overlay events remain background-level continuity signals, not synthetic emergencies.
- The feed can function without the overlay, and the overlay can degrade gracefully without the feed.
- Cursor identity used in overlay handoff remains the same cursor identity used by the attention feed.

# Detailed verification expectations
- Transcript-style e2e scenarios for cold start, warm path, zoom-return loop, agent handoff, watch-mode integration, and degraded/no-feed behavior.
- TUI or screenshot artifacts where they materially help future debugging.
- Diff-friendly diagnostics that identify which invariant failed when a scenario breaks.
- Logs that record cursor values, selected focus targets, emitted human-originated events, overlay state, and degraded-mode markers.

# Acceptance criteria
- [ ] The overlay/feed integration behaves coherently across its main happy paths and degraded paths.
- [ ] The documented invariants are verified, not just asserted.
- [ ] Useful artifacts remain behind for future debugging.
- [ ] Overlay/feed integration remains subordinate to the core attention-feed contract rather than forking it.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-21T01:09:03.851325660Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-21T01:22:21.713555773Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["attention-feed","gate","overlay","phase-3","verification"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"br-a1ti3","depends_on_id":"br-5u235","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T01:10:31.515583773Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-a1ti3","depends_on_id":"br-a6cmp","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T01:10:35.079137474Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-a1ti3","depends_on_id":"br-abp0s","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T01:10:32.921699049Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-a1ti3","depends_on_id":"br-ht8jy","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T01:10:33.661958365Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-a1ti3","depends_on_id":"br-la5zy","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T01:10:34.921653572Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-a1ti3","depends_on_id":"br-rb9oj","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T01:16:15.468849274Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-a1ti3","depends_on_id":"br-ut0d8","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T01:10:32.761963761Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-a1ti3","depends_on_id":"br-x66gc","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-21T01:10:41.208284760Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-a1ti3","depends_on_id":"br-xq4b0","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T01:16:15.141183759Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"br-a6cmp","title":"Overlay-Feed T6: Add --robot-overlay command for agent-initiated human handoff","description":"# Why this bead exists
The attention feed is the sensor side of the operator loop. Sometimes the correct actuator response is not "send another prompt" but "bring the human to the right place." This bead gives robot-mode a structured overlay handoff surface so an agent can do that mechanically instead of resorting to ad hoc human instructions.

# Scope
1. Add a robot-mode command for opening the overlay for a target session with structured JSON success/error behavior.
2. Support an optional attention cursor so the robot command can open the overlay pre-focused on the relevant attention item.
3. Follow existing robot conventions for exit codes, `success`, `timestamp`, and structured errors.
4. Be explicit about whether the command blocks until dismissal or supports a no-wait path; whichever behavior wins must be documented and testable.
5. Keep the command a thin actuator layer over existing overlay functionality rather than inventing another orchestration surface.

# Design considerations
- The command should make human handoff possible without pretending ntm can decide when a human should be involved.
- Blocking versus non-blocking behavior matters operationally and must not be left implicit.
- Failure cases such as not being inside tmux or missing session state must be machine-usable and honest.

# Detailed verification expectations
- Golden tests for success, unavailable, and failure JSON payloads.
- Tests for blocking/no-wait behavior and structured exit-code conventions.
- Integration tests covering cursor-targeted overlay handoff via the T4 surface.
- Transcript scenarios where an agent wakes on attention, decides to involve a human, opens the overlay, and records the resulting handoff artifacts.
- Detailed logs in tests that print session, cursor, blocking mode, emitted JSON, and failure reason.

# Acceptance criteria
- [ ] Robot-mode can open the overlay through a structured, machine-usable command.
- [ ] Cursor-targeted handoff is supported once the overlay focus surface exists.
- [ ] Blocking behavior and error semantics are explicit and tested.
- [ ] Automated tests and transcript artifacts make human-handoff behavior auditable.","status":"open","priority":3,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-21T01:08:39.758756568Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-21T01:15:56.500426883Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["attention-feed","cli","overlay","phase-3","robot"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"br-a6cmp","depends_on_id":"br-ht8jy","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T01:10:49.821416803Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-a6cmp","depends_on_id":"br-x66gc","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-21T01:10:40.039354013Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
-{"id":"br-a6cs7","title":"Phase 2d: Replace Custom List Component with bubbles/list for Pane Navigation","description":"# Replace Inline Pane List Rendering with bubbles/list

## Background — CORRECTED: Dashboard uses INLINE rendering, not components/list
The dashboard pane list is rendered by renderPaneList() at dashboard.go:6497-6518. This calls:
  - CalculateLayout() for dimensions
  - RenderTableHeader() for column headers
  - BuildPaneTableRows() to hydrate row data
  - RenderPaneRow() for each row (with AgentBadge, status, TPM, border colors)

This is ~200 LOC of inline table rendering. components/list.go (486 LOC) is NOT USED by the
dashboard — it's only imported in tests (components_test.go).

Selection state: Model.cursor (int), Model.panes ([]tmux.Pane). Cursor preserved across
refresh via prevSelectedID matching at dashboard.go:2653-2706.

## What Changes
Replace the inline renderPaneList() table rendering with bubbles/list, gaining fuzzy filtering.
This means:
1. renderPaneList(), RenderTableHeader(), BuildPaneTableRows(), RenderPaneRow() become
   the delegate's Render() method
2. Model.cursor → list.Model.Index()
3. Model.panes stays as data source; list items mirror it

## CRITICAL: '/' key is NOT currently bound (verified: grep '/' dashboard.go = 0 hits)

## CRITICAL: SetItems() re-runs filter (verified from bubbles source, line 384-397)
Filter text IS preserved. But cursor position needs explicit restoration by pane ID.

## Implementation Plan

### 1. Define paneItem implementing list.Item
  type paneItem struct {
      pane      tmux.Pane        // underlying data
      agentType string
      status    string
      tpm       int
  }
  func (p paneItem) Title() string       { return p.pane.Title }
  func (p paneItem) Description() string { return fmt.Sprintf("%s | %d tpm", p.status, p.tpm) }
  func (p paneItem) FilterValue() string { return p.pane.Title + " " + p.agentType }

### 2. Custom delegate preserving existing visual design
  type paneDelegate struct {
      theme  *theme.Theme
      icons  *icons.IconSet
      tick   int
      wide   bool  // true in TierWide+ (shows 2-line rows with sub-parts)
  }
  func (d paneDelegate) Height() int {
      if d.wide { return 2 }  // wide tiers show secondLine (badges, locks, etc.)
      return 1                // narrow/split tiers: single line
  }
  func (d paneDelegate) Spacing() int { return 0 }
  func (d paneDelegate) Update(msg tea.Msg, m *list.Model) tea.Cmd { return nil }
  func (d paneDelegate) Render(w io.Writer, m list.Model, index int, item list.Item) {
      p := item.(paneItem)
      // PORT existing RenderPaneRow() logic here (layout.go:508-736)
      // The row rendering is ~230 lines — the delegate Render becomes the new home.
      // Must handle: border color, selection indicator, index badge, type icon,
      // title, status, TPM, activity dot, lock icon, bead counts, model badge.
      // In wide mode: secondLine with sub-parts (badges, locks, comments, model).
  }

  NOTE: RenderPaneRow is ~230 LOC of rendering logic. The delegate Render() must
  port ALL of it, not simplify. The visual output must be identical to current.
  Key concern: RenderPaneRow uses LayoutDimensions for column widths — the delegate
  must compute or receive equivalent dimensions from the panel width.

### 3. Migrate cursor tracking
  OLD: m.cursor int + m.panes[]tmux.Pane
  NEW: m.paneList list.Model (contains items, selection, filter state)
  Keep m.panes as data source; rebuild list items on refresh.

### 4. Selection preservation during refresh
  func (m *Model) refreshPaneList(newPanes []tmux.Pane) tea.Cmd {
      // Save current selection by pane ID
      var prevID string
      if sel := m.paneList.SelectedItem(); sel != nil {
          prevID = sel.(paneItem).pane.ID
      }
      // Build new items
      items := make([]list.Item, len(newPanes))
      for i, p := range newPanes { items[i] = toPaneItem(p, m.paneStatus) }
      // Update (re-applies filter automatically)
      cmd := m.paneList.SetItems(items)
      // Restore selection by ID
      if prevID != "" {
          for i, item := range m.paneList.Items() {
              if item.(paneItem).pane.ID == prevID { m.paneList.Select(i); break }
          }
      }
      return cmd
  }

### 5. Replace renderPaneList() calls with m.paneList.View()
  Remove or deprecate: renderPaneList(), RenderTableHeader(), BuildPaneTableRows(),
  RenderPaneRow() — but KEEP RenderPaneRow logic in delegate.

### 6. Route messages
  When pane list panel is focused, route all messages through m.paneList.Update(msg).

## Unit Tests (REQUIRED)

### New file: internal/tui/dashboard/pane_list_test.go
  func TestPaneItemInterface(t *testing.T) {
      p := paneItem{pane: tmux.Pane{Title: "proj__cc_1"}, agentType: "claude", status: "working", tpm: 150}
      if p.Title() != "proj__cc_1" { t.Error("wrong title") }
      if p.FilterValue() == "" { t.Error("empty filter value") }
      if !strings.Contains(p.FilterValue(), "claude") { t.Error("agent type missing from filter") }
  }

  func TestPaneDelegateRender(t *testing.T) {
      d := paneDelegate{theme: theme.Default(), icons: icons.Default()}
      items := []list.Item{
          paneItem{pane: tmux.Pane{Title: "proj__cc_1", Type: tmux.AgentClaude}},
          paneItem{pane: tmux.Pane{Title: "proj__cod_1", Type: tmux.AgentCodex}},
      }
      l := list.New(items, d, 60, 10)
      view := l.View()
      if view == "" { t.Error("list should render") }
  }

  func TestPaneListRefreshPreservesSelection(t *testing.T) {
      items := []list.Item{
          paneItem{pane: tmux.Pane{ID: "1", Title: "cc_1"}},
          paneItem{pane: tmux.Pane{ID: "2", Title: "cc_2"}},
          paneItem{pane: tmux.Pane{ID: "3", Title: "cod_1"}},
      }
      l := list.New(items, paneDelegate{}, 60, 20)
      l.Select(1) // select cc_2
      // Simulate refresh with reordered items
      newItems := []list.Item{
          paneItem{pane: tmux.Pane{ID: "1", Title: "cc_1"}},
          paneItem{pane: tmux.Pane{ID: "3", Title: "cod_1"}},
          paneItem{pane: tmux.Pane{ID: "2", Title: "cc_2"}},  // moved
          paneItem{pane: tmux.Pane{ID: "4", Title: "cc_3"}},  // new
      }
      l.SetItems(newItems)
      // Find cc_2 by ID and restore
      for i, item := range l.Items() {
          if item.(paneItem).pane.ID == "2" { l.Select(i); break }
      }
      if l.SelectedItem().(paneItem).pane.ID != "2" { t.Error("selection not preserved") }
  }

  func TestPaneListEmptyState(t *testing.T) {
      l := list.New(nil, paneDelegate{}, 60, 20)
      view := l.View()
      if view == "" { t.Error("empty list should render") }
  }

  func TestPaneListFilterKey(t *testing.T) {
      // '/' is the default filter key in bubbles/list
      items := []list.Item{
          paneItem{pane: tmux.Pane{Title: "proj__cc_1"}, agentType: "claude"},
          paneItem{pane: tmux.Pane{Title: "proj__cod_1"}, agentType: "codex"},
      }
      l := list.New(items, paneDelegate{}, 60, 20)
      l.SetFilteringEnabled(true)
      // Verify filtering is enabled
      if !l.FilteringEnabled() { t.Error("filtering should be enabled") }
  }

  func BenchmarkPaneListView(b *testing.B) {
      items := make([]list.Item, 20)
      for i := range items {
          items[i] = paneItem{pane: tmux.Pane{ID: fmt.Sprintf("%d",i), Title: fmt.Sprintf("proj__cc_%d",i)}}
      }
      l := list.New(items, paneDelegate{}, 60, 20)
      b.ResetTimer()
      for i := 0; i < b.N; i++ { _ = l.View() }
  }

## E2E / VHS Verification
Create testdata/vhs/dashboard-fuzzy-filter.tape:
  Type "/" to enter filter mode, type "cc", verify filtering, Esc to clear.

## Logging
- Log pane list init: "pane list: %d items, filter=true, delegate=paneDelegate"
- Log refresh: "pane list: refreshed %d items, selection=%s preserved=%v"
- Log filter activation: "pane list: filter mode active, query='%s'"
- Debug log selection changes: "pane list: selected index=%d id=%s"

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] bubbles/list replaces inline renderPaneList() table rendering
- [ ] paneDelegate reuses existing AgentBadge/StatusBadge visual design
- [ ] Fuzzy filtering via '/' key (no key conflict)
- [ ] Selection preserved across refresh (by pane ID)
- [ ] Filter text preserved across refresh (bubbles handles this)
- [ ] Status bar shows item count
- [ ] Empty state renders gracefully
- [ ] All existing dashboard_layout_test.go (1900 LOC) tests pass
- [ ] All 6 new tests + benchmark pass
- [ ] VHS shows filtering

## Files to Modify
- internal/tui/dashboard/dashboard.go (replace cursor with list.Model, route messages)
- internal/tui/dashboard/layout.go (remove RenderTableHeader/BuildPaneTableRows/RenderPaneRow)

## Files to Create
- internal/tui/dashboard/pane_delegate.go (delegate + paneItem — genuinely new type)

Tests go in existing dashboard_layout_test.go (1900 LOC) — no new test file.
(AGENTS.md: no file proliferation)

## Risk: MEDIUM-HIGH — Primary navigation. 1900 LOC of layout tests may need updates.
Delegate must reproduce exact visual design of current RenderPaneRow().

## SEQUENCING NOTE  
This bead runs AFTER Phase 2c (viewport) because: (1) both heavily modify
dashboard.go — 2c adds truncateToHeight bypass, this bead replaces the entire
pane list rendering; (2) 2c adds HandlesOwnHeight() to the Panel interface,
which must be stable before this bead modifies the dashboard further.
