 {"id":"br-auag6","title":"Attention Feed Phase 4a2: Add attention-aware dashboard and terse views","description":"# Why this bead exists
Help/capabilities teach the contract, but dashboard and terse output are where humans and low-token agent loops actually glance first. If those surfaces are not attention-aware, the product still feels fragmented even if the underlying feed is sound. This bead makes the human-facing summary surfaces legible without inventing a second taxonomy.

# Scope
1. Introduce one shared attention-summary/view-model for live summaries so dashboard, terse output, and any later overlay integrations do not each invent their own classification logic.
2. Add an attention-aware section to `--robot-dashboard` that highlights the same frontier an operator agent would care about: active attention items, compact counts, and honest degraded/unsupported markers.
3. Update `--robot-terse` so it can surface meaningful attention state within very tight token limits without collapsing into noisy sludge.
4. Ensure dashboard/terse summaries respect the same signal taxonomy and supported profiles/presets as events, digest, wait, and attention.
5. Keep the summary shallow: these views should orient the user quickly and point toward follow-up surfaces, not duplicate the full digest or raw event feed.
6. If the TUI/dashboard has sensible integration points, reuse the same summary/view-model there instead of maintaining a forked representation.

# Design considerations
- Humans and agents should converge on the same frontier, not learn different notions of what matters.
- Terse output has severe token constraints, so every field must earn its place.
- Summary surfaces should degrade honestly when some conditions are unsupported or partially observable.
- Any shared summary/view-model introduced here should make later overlay work simpler, not couple it to a separate ad hoc cache.

# Detailed verification expectations
- Golden tests for dashboard and terse output in quiet, interesting, action-required, and degraded states.
- Tests that compare dashboard/terse summaries against the underlying signal state under the same active profile.
- Tests that prove terse output stays compact while still surfacing the most important frontier change.
- Transcript or TUI artifact scenarios showing dashboard and terse output before and after meaningful attention transitions.
- Diff-friendly diagnostics when summary buckets, profile resolution, or degraded markers drift unexpectedly.
- Detailed logs in tests that print active profile, bucket counts, suppressed counts, and the exact summary fragments emitted.

# Acceptance criteria
- [ ] Dashboard and terse output make the attention frontier easier to understand in practice.
- [ ] Summary surfaces are driven by the same real signal taxonomy and profile semantics as the rest of the attention-feed system.
- [ ] Degraded or unsupported behavior is represented honestly.
- [ ] Automated tests and artifact-generating scenarios make regressions obvious.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","assignee":"BrightForge","estimated_minutes":150,"created_at":"2026-03-21T01:05:01.330433316Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-21T09:14:52.215801978Z","closed_at":"2026-03-21T09:14:52.214262575Z","close_reason":"done","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["attention-feed","dashboard","ergonomics","phase-4","robot","terse"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"br-auag6","depends_on_id":"br-91gti","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T01:11:29.184480732Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-auag6","depends_on_id":"br-slg9g","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T01:11:28.938744644Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"br-bgfdt","title":"Phase 1 VERIFY: Run Full TUI Inspector Suite — Compare to Baselines","description":"# Phase 1 Verification Gate

## Purpose
After all Phase 1 tasks complete, verify no regressions.

## Mandatory Steps

### 1. Build verification
  go build ./cmd/ntm 2>&1 | tee /tmp/gate1_build.log
  go vet ./internal/tui/... 2>&1 | tee /tmp/gate1_vet.log

### 2. Unit test regression check
  go test -v -count=1 -short ./internal/tui/... 2>&1 | tee /tmp/gate1_tests.log
  # Count passing tests
  PASS_COUNT=$(grep -c '^--- PASS' /tmp/gate1_tests.log)
  BASELINE_COUNT=$(grep -c '^--- PASS' /tmp/tui_test_baseline.log)
  echo "Tests: phase1=$PASS_COUNT baseline=$BASELINE_COUNT"
  # PASS_COUNT must be >= BASELINE_COUNT (may be higher due to new tests)
  if [ "$PASS_COUNT" -lt "$BASELINE_COUNT" ]; then
      echo "ERROR: Test count regression! $PASS_COUNT < $BASELINE_COUNT"
      exit 1
  fi

### 3. VHS capture suite
  bash /dp/tui_inspector/scripts/run_ntm_tui_suite.sh \
    --profiles ntm-dashboard-empty,ntm-dashboard-help,ntm-dashboard-navigate,ntm-dashboard-wide,ntm-palette \
    --suite-name "phase1_post_upgrade"

### 4. Snapshot comparison
  For each profile, compare phase1 vs previous phase snapshots.
  Log any visual differences.

### 5. Log summary
