-{"id":"br-byln7","title":"Attention Feed Epic: Event-driven robot nervous system for frontier LLM operators","description":"# Why this initiative exists
ntm already has a strong robot mode, but the agent-facing surfaces are fragmented. A frontier LLM can drive the system today, yet it has to poll heavily, reconcile multiple partial views, and infer which changes actually deserve attention. The goal of this initiative is to make ntm a much better nervous system for an intelligent operator without turning ntm into a second coordinator.

# Architectural position
This work must remain fully compatible with the existing flywheel approach:
- beads remains the execution substrate and issue graph
- Agent Mail remains the coordination / reservation layer
- bv remains the prioritization and graph-triage layer
- the frontier LLM remains the actual driver / decision-maker
- ntm becomes better at sensing change, surfacing deltas, and exposing precise machine interfaces

# What success looks like
A tending agent should be able to:
1. take a cold-start snapshot,
2. remember a cursor boundary,
3. sleep until something important happens,
4. wake up with a compact digest,
5. inspect only the exact surface that now needs judgment,
6. resync cleanly when replay is no longer possible.

That should reduce token burn, reduce wasteful polling, and make one operator agent capable of tending more sessions without hidden orchestration logic.

# Intended deliverables
This initiative covers:
- a normalized event envelope and cursor model
- a cursor-bearing snapshot bootstrap path
- a replayable raw event feed
- a compact digest view for deltas
- richer named wait conditions
- a one-obvious-way attention macro
- server / SSE / WebSocket parity
- dashboard/help/capabilities integration
- comprehensive automated verification with detailed logs

# Explicit non-goals
- No mission engine
- No second task graph
- No replacement for beads, Agent Mail, or bv
- No hidden overseer state that becomes load-bearing
- No free-form mini-language for wait predicates when a named condition set is sufficient
- No schema split where CLI, HTTP, and WebSocket expose incompatible shapes

# Roll-up behavior
This bead is a roll-up epic, not an independently actionable implementation task. It should remain blocked on the final validation gate so `bv` does not surface it as ready work ahead of the real implementation beads.

# Future-self note
If this initiative ever starts looking like "ntm is becoming the planner," stop and re-scope it. The whole point is to improve the mechanical sensor/actuator layer around an intelligent driver, not to encode the driver's intelligence inside ntm.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"epic","estimated_minutes":180,"created_at":"2026-03-21T00:49:19.007969934Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-21T00:57:16.416512232Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["architecture","attention-feed","epic","operator-loop","robot"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"br-byln7","depends_on_id":"br-7h8it","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-21T00:57:16.415594003Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
